Creates a binary tree seeded by this value

  free_bittree(local_d0);
A binary tree is a data structure where each node can have up to two children:

left child
right child
At the very top is the root node

           [5]
          /   \
       [2]     [7]
       / \     / \
    (1)  (6) (3) (4)

Squares are internal node (with children)
Circle are leaves (no children)



Calls shadow_tree_mix(tree, &amp;local_f0, &amp;local_f4) function to walk the tree and produce local_f0 (accumulator: collects a sequence of 3-bit chunks from each leaf)  and local_f4 (leaf count: tells you how many leaves contributed to that sequence.)


free_bittree(tree) → free memory.


local_c8 = shadow_protocol(local_f0) → turn the accumulator into an 8-byte keystream mask.


Read flag.txt and XOR each flag byte with the corresponding byte of local_c8(byte index modulo 8) and print hex


Once we know the principal logic of this program we can try to understand the two functions in charge of creating our XOR key:

