All this information adds up to :

We have the actual flag in flag.txt
The flag is being XORed with an 8-byte key
This key is derived from the actual time of the script’s execution

This means that based on the basic principles of XOR, we could just re-run the program with the encrypted key as input, and using the time given from the output of the program. Which will give us the flag in plaintext
Here is a small diagram:
Encryption:                    Decryption:
 -----------                    ------------
 Plaintext ⊕ Key = Ciphertext    Ciphertext ⊕ Key = Plaintext

   P ⊕ K = C                        C ⊕ K = P

The program will run:
FLAG byte   ⊕   KEY byte   =   ENCRYPTED byte

And to recover:
ENCRYPTED byte   ⊕   KEY byte   =   FLAG byte

