Similar to: washi1337.github.io/ctf-writeups/writeups/flare-on/2019/8/
In this challenge, the main loop waits for a jump action. Each valid jump will increment the jump counter (local_18). When the counter exceeds MAX_JUMP_COUNT is set to 1 and the loop ends. Once this is done, the function FUN190320252011() is called, which opens up the Flag. The goal s to force the condition.

Jump counter (local_18):

local_10 = -0x16;
local_11 = &#039;\0&#039;;
local_18 = local_18 + 1;
if (MAX_JUMP_COUNT &lt;= local_18) {
  local_a = &#039;\x01&#039;;
  local_9 = &#039;\0&#039;;
}
Once this reaches MAX_JUMP_COUNT the code checks:
if (local_a != &#039;\0&#039;) {
  FUN190320252011();
}

Localization of the binary instruction:
When we select the function in ghidra we can see the instruction which looks like:

001016a7 39 45 f0        CMP        dword ptr [RBP + local_18],EAX
001016aa 7c 08           JL         LAB_001016b4
001016ac c6 45 fe 01     MOV        byte ptr [RBP + local_a],0x1
001016b0 c6 45 ff 00     MOV        byte ptr [RBP + local_9],0x0
the JL instruction is a conditional jump used in comparisons and in loops. In this case it is the instruction that is checking if the jump counter is below MAX_JUMP_COUNT.
We can replace it with NOP instruction(no operation - it consumes one CPU cycle, and then moves to the next instruction), in order to remove the conditional check that could make the program loop to the infinite. This is setting the variable that break out of the loop.
The original instruction made the CPU jump around the loop-exiting code (the loop continues)
Without the jump, the CPU falls through and executes the instructions that signal “end of the loop” (local_a = 1)
IN order to patch this we open
cp Jumploit Jumploit_patch
hexedit Jumploit_pats
/7c08  # this corresponds to the Jump instruction in hex
9090   # replace with NOP instruction
ctrl+x
y

