In order to bypass it, first we will need to upload frida server into the android device. It is important to note that the version of frida on your pc and the version of frida server on the emulated device must be the same, and must align with the architecture of the device:

First verify the installed version of Frida

frida --version  
15.1.17

Verify the architecture of the emulated phone

adb devices  
List of devices attached  
emulator-5554   device  

adb shell  
generic_x86_arm:/ # uname -m  
i686  
generic_x86_arm:/ #
i686 corresponds to x86 system (32-Bit) so I will need to install a server for this architecture, If the response had been x86_64 it would mean that the system is a x64 (64-bit). In order to get a valid frida server here is the official repo : github.com/frida/frida/releases
I downloaded the following version : frida-server-15.1.17-android-x86 and did the following commands :
unxz frida-server-15.1.17-android-x86
chmod +x frida-server-15.1.17-android-x86
adb push frida-server-15.1.17-android-x86 /data/local/tmp/
Now once that we have our frida server on the android emulator we can launch frida and start using it’s functionalities
